<br>
Check out the following question: “Why is it when you talk to God its called prayer, but when he talks to you its called schizophrenia?”<br>
<br>
Also, consider the following true story: a few weeks ago I took a road trip with a good friend of mine, in which we traveled through several states - one of them happened to be Utah. One of our stops was at a historic fort from the mid 1800’s. Because of the strong Mormon influence in Utah it had been a Mormon built and operated fort. As I expected, a Mormon “Elder” was at the fort giving free tours of the building. While he showed us the grounds I saw everything from several pictures of Joseph Smith to a couple Books of Mormon lying around in the rooms. After politely enduring the tour, he showed us several Books of Mormon that had been translated into different languages. Then, (I knew this part was coming next) he asked us if we’d like a copy. Before my friend could say anything, I quickly said “That’s okay, he’s a Catholic and I’m an Atheist’ Needless to say after we got back on the road our topic matter discussed inside the car soon turned to religion. We have been friends for about 3 years now, but he somehow never caught on that I was an Atheist until that “fateful” day. Well, after I officially “came out” about my rational thinking, all I can say is that you would have loved to listen to a tape of that conversation! Perhaps the most interesting aspect of the conversation is that aside from a few questions he said nothing the entire time I talked about the issue, which was around a full ten minutes. The conversation went something like the: <br>
<br>
Friend: “Its really cool how they (Mormons) stand behind their religion”<br>
<br>
Me: “Umm, yeah ah its actually kind of sad they can believe so strongly in such utter crap”<br>
<br>
Friend: “So you’re an Atheist eh?” (Surprised tone of voice)<br>
<br>
Me: “Well, my parents are Christians and they tried to raise me that way, but as I grew older I started to question living in blind faith to a religion that most Westerners just happen to believe because they were born into a culture that has believed Christianity for so long.”<br>
<br>
Friend: (looks out window)<br>
<br>
Me: “I mean how do you know Catholicism will get you to heaven or is the “right” thing to believe in? Because you’re parents and others around you have always told you so? What about the religion of the native tribes before the Spaniards came over? That’s not the “right” religion anymore? (He’s Mexican)<br>
<br>
Friend: (twitches, not knowing what to say)<br>
<br>
Me: “Think about how the Third World is so much more dependent upon religion then the more advanced Industrial nations. They depend on “God” to cure sickness, make the rain to fall on their crops, give them a house, a job, money, keep bad spirits away etc. We here in the states don’t need all that, because we have technology that has in essence replaced “God” so that the crutch and weakness of religion no longer holds such importance in living day to day life.”<br>
<br>
Friend: (sighs, says “oh boy”, looks out window again)<br>
<br>
Me: “What about all the different religions in the world? Which one is going to get you into heaven? I mean if you’re born into a culture that has one kind religion how do you know that religion X of another culture is the one you should really believe in? <br>
<br>
Friend: (looks to be irritated)<br>
<br>
Me: “And then there’s the issue of the Gods of old. What of the Roman Gods and other ancient Gods? They just don’t cut it anymore? I Guess humans had to “update” God to fit the changing picture, instead of several Gods we just needed one. And what of the future? Is “God” going to have to be “upgraded” again?<br>
<br>
Friend: (rolls his eyes)<br>
<br>
Me: “What does “God” do for you anyway? What do you need or use him for? <br>
<br>
Friend: (says nothing; he’s what I call a “Fad Catholic”, not devout, just believes in it because he’s never questioned what it means or why it is so.)<br>
<br>
Me: “I’m an Atheist because I wasn’t about to blindly follow the rest of the crowd, something that wasn’t easy. All my friends and acquaintances up to that point were Christians. But I knew after searching that “God” is in fact a subjective reality and a figment of the human imagination. Usually, depending on how hard a person’s living environment is, will determine how strong their religious beliefs are.”<br>
<br>
Friend: (shuffles feet, clears throat)<br>
<br>
Me: “And then there is the endless strife that religion causes, just look at the Israelis and Palestinians or the conflict in Ireland. I mean, don’t you think that energy could be better expended toward something more worthwhile, such as finding a cure for cancer? Or how about if the Israelis and Palestinians could work together to make desalinization a reality and put an end to water storages?”<br>
<br>
Friend: (losing interest fast)<br>
<br>
Me: “Another thing that bothered me was how historically, the church would burn people at the state or put them under house arrest, just because that didn’t believe that the Earth was at the center of the universe. In fact, this ignorance of common sense and rational thinking among religion is still very prevalent today.” <br>
<br>
Friend: (Gets phone call on cell phone, changes his demeanor at once)<br>
<br>
Me: (Thinks to self) “Its no use.”<br>
<br>
<br>
************************************************************************ <br>
Well, that may seem like the end of the story, but it wasn’t. A few days later we were camping in one of the Redwood forests of California. It wasn’t my first time camping in the Redwoods, but I was still in awe. These trees, hundreds of years old, were around before Columbus sailed for the New World. I thought to myself how many generations in my own family tree I’d have to count back in order to reach the year the bigger trees where just little saplings. My mind was also filled with many other thoughts, such as how much a single large tree would weigh, how the leaves fall and make a natural fertilizer for the roots, the sheer size of these living organisms, the natural resistance to fire a Redwood tree has, the unique wildlife that lives in and among the trees, how the trees continue their legacy by the dropping of tiny seeds that in turn grow into such immense life forms, etc. <br>
All of this significance was seemly lost on my friend who had no comments, questions or the slightest inquisitiveness. Nevertheless, I couldn’t help but say out loud some of the things that were going through my mind at the time.<br>
   <br>
We started a fire in the fire ring and I proceeded to cook an egg omelet, which required some seasonings, among them salt. In a playful manner I shook the saltshaker in the direction of my cohort, who immediately said in a serous voice something to the effect of “Hey don’t get any salt on me or the angels wont want to be near me” I instantly recognized this statement as being a Catholic superstition and I made the mistake of saying so. My friend angrily retorted, “You’re the one that’s crazy!” and stomped off into the tent in a bad disposition. How many other Catholic superstitions there are I don’t want to know, but the fact remains that those who refuse to open their eyes and minds to reality will linger in the borderlands of blind faith of God and belief in the supernatural as an excuse to not be inquisitive into the mysteries of the world around us. Thus, in one fell swoop the entire proven methods of science can be discounted by a religious person as “pagan” “blasphemous” or “ungodly.”<br>
<br>
This is not the kind of world my successor generation is going to live in if I can help it.<br>
On one hand my friend holds that any belief in God is contrary to natural human nature, but on the other hand he couldn’t even lift his head and mind to “God’s creation” of the Redwood trees – a disturbing negation. <br>
<br>
It can be said with absolute certainly that religion in the Western Hemisphere is on the demise. Without question, as science increasingly answers additional questions and yields important clues about life as we know it, religion will likely go the way of the dinosaurs. Religion and God cannot compete with air conditioning, reliable transportation, medical wonders, abundant food, the personal computer, etc. The dependency on God is directly linked to human wants and needs. Minus those wants and needs and you minus God out of the picture. Indeed, the “holdout” religious nations of the world today display an almost unbelievable backwardness and inept value of human life (Middle Eastern nations, for example). In the near future as is the case now, those religions that do survive and their institutions, will become mainly “social clubs” for people to gather in and around, the original religious fervor all but a ghost of its former self. I was rather offensively reminded of this very fact as a drove past a brand new church in Santa Barbara, CA. This church had to have cost tens of millions of dollars to construct and furbish. Out in the front, draped across the front door, was a large white banner with red lettering, it read: “Grand Opening this Sunday” as if it was a new Wal Mart opening for business. I almost drove off the road. <br>
<br>
Well, this post has become much longer then I originally intended. As always, I look forward to your replies.   <br>
